{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17411375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17411375"},"attributes":{"position":2,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14228"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477330"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:59:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:59:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14228"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260986"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T06:24:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:02:58+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":13,"questionsAnswered":0,"marksTotal":0,"marksAttainable":0,"marksAttempted":0,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T06:25:33+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"14228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14228"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.11,0.05,0.39,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6915"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54149"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6915"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14228"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39621"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1641"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15835"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37421"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54149"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of breathlessness and bluish discolouration of the skin. He has a known history of Tetralogy of Fallot and is awaiting corrective surgery. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with marked cyanosis. His pulse rate is 160/min, respiratory rate 60/min, SpO2 70% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals a harsh systolic murmur at the left sternal border. The emergency physician recognises this as a hypercyanotic spell and immediately places the infant in a knee-to-chest position.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains the physiological basis for using the knee-to-chest position in this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased venous return to the heart","Decreased pulmonary arterial resistance","Increased pulmonary arterial resistance","Increased systemic vascular resistance","Decreased systemic vascular resistance"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe knee-to-chest position is a crucial initial management step for hypercyanotic spells in patients with Tetralogy of Fallot (TOF). This position works primarily by \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing systemic vascular resistance\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the correct answer and the key physiological mechanism behind its effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased systemic vascular resistance\u003C/strong\u003E would actually worsen the hypercyanotic spell by promoting more right-to-left shunting across the ventricular septal defect (VSD), and is therefore incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased pulmonary arterial resistance\u003C/strong\u003E would also exacerbate the spell by further limiting pulmonary blood flow, which is already compromised in TOF due to right ventricular outflow tract obstruction. This option is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased pulmonary arterial resistance\u003C/strong\u003E, while beneficial in managing hypercyanotic spells, is not the primary effect of the knee-to-chest position. Other interventions, such as oxygen therapy, can help decrease pulmonary vascular resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased venous return to the heart\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially occurring to some degree with this position, is not the primary mechanism by which it improves oxygenation in hypercyanotic spells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn Tetralogy of Fallot, hypercyanotic spells occur due to a sudden increase in right-to-left shunting across the VSD, leading to decreased pulmonary blood flow and worsening cyanosis. By increasing systemic vascular resistance, the knee-to-chest position reduces this right-to-left shunting, thereby improving pulmonary blood flow and oxygenation. This position is a temporary measure while preparing for other interventions such as oxygen therapy, volume expansion, morphine administration, and potentially phenylephrine to further increase systemic vascular resistance. Ultimately, these patients require definitive surgical correction of their cardiac defects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The knee-to-chest position in hypercyanotic spells of Tetralogy of Fallot increases systemic vascular resistance, which reduces right-to-left shunting and improves oxygenation.","Hypercyanotic spells in Tetralogy of Fallot are characterised by sudden worsening of cyanosis due to increased right-to-left shunting across the ventricular septal defect.","Management of hypercyanotic spells in Tetralogy of Fallot includes measures to increase systemic vascular resistance and decrease pulmonary vascular resistance."],"references":["Wilson R, Ross O, Griksaitis MJ. Tetralogy of Fallot. BJA Educ. 2019 Nov;19(11):362-369. Available at: https://www.bjaed.org/article/S2058-5349(19)30122-2/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39621"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14228"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39621"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-30T16:10:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-30T16:11:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6915"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54149"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","nam